"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-2024-02-27-caroline-marks-surfing-taming-the-wave\", \"text\": \"Her ears were bleeding. It was February 2023, at Sunset Beach on Hawai\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099i\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s North Shore midway through the World Surf League Championship Tour\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s second event of the season, when Caroline Marks woke up feeling like something was stabbing her face from the inside. Her pillow was soaked in blood. On her way to the hospital, she couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t stop crying.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSo much pain,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says now, during an early-January drive north on the Pacific Coast Highway from her home in San Clemente, Calif., to Salt Creek Beach in Dana Point. Her ear canals had closed and ruptured, she explains. Issues related to her deviated septum and an influx of seawater had created infections in her sinuses, adenoids and ears.  That night, the doctor ordered immediate surgery. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWell,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she replied, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI have to surf.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  She returned to finish the event in second place, passing off her illness to reporters as a mild ear infection. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was so gnarly,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Marks says now, laughing. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSohectic.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s O.K. now. After the WSL Finals in September\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094when she won her first world championship\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094Marks had surgery in October, fixing her deviated septum and removing her adenoids. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll probably still need my ears drilled soon,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cbut at least my nose is working right now. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve been able to breathe way better. I didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t realize I couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t breathe that well until now.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a fitting metaphor for the 22-year-old superstar. Afterbecoming a globally recognized phenom as young as 13, Marks endured an experience all too familiar for celebrity wunderkinds. She found herself\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and her surfing\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094suffocating under the weight of the world\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s expectations. What she did over the past year wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t just an incredible performance. It was a reclamation of herself.  About that performance. After forgoing surgery in February, Marks surfed through the next eight months of the season, winning three times and finishing in the top five in eight of nine events. She qualified forthe Paris Olympicsand won that world title, fulfilling what had long seemed to be her surfing destiny. Marks has dominated the sport at every level since she was 11. At 13, she became the youngest surfer to appear in a WSL Champions Tour event. In 2021, at 19, she was the youngest surfer in the Olympics. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe potential has been there for years,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d 11-time WSL champion Kelly Slater said in September. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s great to see it come together.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  The world title came after a year when Marks\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s surfing future seemed in doubt: She stepped away from the tour for several months in 2022 to do a full reset for her mind and her life, leaving California for some much-needed time with family in her home state of Florida. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cEvery moment away from the tour felt like an eternity,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBut that made me really focus on what I needed to focus on, and not run away from it.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Born on Valentine\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Day 2002 in Boca Raton, Fla., Marks grew up in Melbourne Beach, on Florida\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s east coast. Darren and Sarah Marks already had three sons; Caroline\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s arrival made Sarah cry in joy. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cOh yay,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she recalls thinking. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe can do girly stuff!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Sarah loved horses and introduced Caroline early. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBraids and pink boots,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. By the age of 7, Caroline excelled at barrel racing. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe had no fear,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says her brother Luke, three years her senior.  The Marks were an active bunch. Surfing, horses, motocross, skateboarding\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094they had a full halfpipe along with a dirt track right in their backyard. And Caroline had energy to burn. When Sarah went for walks on the beach, Caroline \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cran laps around me,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Sarah says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cfor miles and miles.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  At 8, Caroline\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s love of horses gave way to passion for the waves. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAll she would say,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d recalls Sarah, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cis, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098I wanna be with my brothers, I wanna be with my brothers!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Luke, the family\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s best surfer, gave her an old board. They took her out on a Friday afternoon. She caught waves by the end of Day 1, riding what\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s known as goofy-footed, right foot forward instead of the traditional left. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cJust felt better,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI went with it.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  By Saturday she cruised, riding waves with ease. By Monday, she carved, making sharp, controlled turns. Every day afterward, she crossed the backyard for the beach and waves beyond. She hung posters featuring surfers likeCarissa Moore, the Hawaiian who won her first world title in 2011 at age 18, when Caroline was 9. When her grandfather offered to buy her a horse, she declined, saying she just wanted to surf now.  Soon Caroline didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t just surf with her brothers; she tried to beat them. Some sessions ended in tears, but she always went back. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThey were hard on me, but it came from love,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThey saw something in me. And I just wanted to impress them, make them gowhoa!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  In her very first competitive event, a neighborhood contest, 9-year-old Caroline beat everyone her age, boys and girls. She finished fourth the event after that, a result shehated so much she wanted to quit. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cYou can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t quit,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Luke told her. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cYou\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re too good.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  She didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t quit, but after that she trashed any trophy that wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t first place. During competitions, she surfed even while waiting for her heats, catching every wave she could. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe have a term for surfers like that,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Darren, a longtime amateur surfer himself. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThey\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098frothing.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d They can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t get enough.  At age 11, Caroline put herself on the surf world map. She swept the U-12, U-14 and U-16 divisions at the Atlantic Surfing Federation championships at Sebastian Inlet, Fla., where she also caught her first barrel. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe ultimate goal as a surfer,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. It takes most surfers years to catch one. Team USA signed her within a week, its younger surfer ever. The following year, at the National Scholastic Surfing Association championships in Huntington Beach, Calif.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094the country\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s largest amateur competition\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094Caroline won the all-ages women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Open contest. Surfing in a powerful squat, with strong legs and a low center of gravity, she overshadowed the best amateurs in the country and carved the tops off California\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s larger waves with ease, even at her young age. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHer feet seemed stuck to the board,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says retired pro surfer Mike Parsons. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cNothing could knock her off her board.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Parsons soon became her coach and agent. Over the next few years, Caroline ripped through amateur competition, winning more than a dozen national and international titles across a slew of ages and divisions. Along the way, at 13, she became the youngest surfer to make the WSL Champions Tour, the sport\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s highest level of competition, after receiving a wild-card placement at Lower Trestles, a breathtaking and iconic location with a gorgeous beach and waves that break long and high and smooth. Suddenly Caroline found herself in a heat against Moore, the hero from her posters. And she held her own.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe was this radical little spark plug of a power surfer,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Matt Biolos, founder of the Lost surfboard company and apparel brand and Marks\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s exclusive board maker since she went pro. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s like a Simone Biles. Whatever she tells her body to do, it does it well.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Most of her competitors used boards with thinner, curved rockers to help them gain speed and power on the wave. Caroline was so strong she needed the opposite; Biolos made her boards increasingly thicker and nearly flat. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe needs the resistance,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he says.  By 16, Caroline made the tour full-time and soon became known as its happiest surfer. Cold and rainy conditions would leave everyone miserable\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094except Caroline, who\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099d smile and laugh, going, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIsn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t this great, you guys? Isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t this great?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe just drove everyone nuts,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Parsons says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThen she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099d hit the water and go full assassin mode.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Marks finished her first full season ranked No. 7 in the world and was named WSL Rookie of the Year in 2018. In the season opener the following year, she defeated Moore in the final heat to claim her first career WSL win. At 17, she became the No. 1\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093ranked surfer in the world.  Now everyone noticed her. Her Instagram following skyrocketed. When she casually went surfing in San Clemente, people knew her in the water. Most of it was good. But some of it wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t. And what wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t good got to her.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cYou have people that love you, and you have people that hate you,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Marks says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAnd you have people that think you look good, and you know, people that think you don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t look good. And that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hard, because to me, there could be 99 positive comments, but it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s so easy to fixate on the negative one.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Then there was Instagram. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAnyone in the world can get into your phone now, right in your pocket,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Caroline says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWhich can be amazing! But sometimes \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d She laughs. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSometimes, really not good! You just do your best to block it out. It was all so new to me and it was shocking, like, people can really be this way? It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s like, you know you should just ignore them, but it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hard.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Marks quit reading social media comments, and, when she turned 18, she posed for the Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Issue, trying to kill her fears by embracing them. She moved into a home she purchased in the hills overlooking San Clemente, claiming a sense of strength from the independence of living alone for the first time.  Still, breaking free of the expectations that came with stardom was difficult. With people constantly telling her how great she would be or should be, she says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI started to feel like I was letting people down if I lost.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  She just trained and surfed, obsessed. No parties, no prom, not even nice restaurants on the road. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was just the hotel to the beach and back,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says.  Marks finished 2019 as No. 2 in the world, just behind Moore, and made the \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009920 Tokyo Olympics. When COVID-19 hit and postponed the Games to \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009921, Marks coped by training twice a day. At the Olympics, she recorded the highest score of any surfer there, male or female. But two rounds later she lost, placing fourth and failing to medal.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThat was rough,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. She began breaking down. Smiled less, stressed more, doubted herself like never before, didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t feel good in the water, and spent less time in it. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI just wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t having fun,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Marks says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAnd then I was feeling guilty about that. That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s where I really struggled, too. I was like,Why do I feel like this when I have this dream life?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Marks had long conversations with her family about stepping away. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was really confusing,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cLike, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098What\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s going on? Why don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t I feel like I normally do?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 I was just lost in the sauce, and it was bleeding through a lot of other things that led me to a really dark place.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI think if you don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t take a break and reset,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d her father told her, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cthen you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re going to stop liking surfing, and even get bitter at it.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  She kept pushing, kept surfing, not wanting to let anyone down. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTrying,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Darren says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cto be what people wanted her to be instead of what she was.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  The 2022 season opened in January at Pipeline on Hawai'i\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s North Shore, where sharp coral reefs wait just below massive, fast-crashing waves. Marks had no feel for the ocean anymore. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe looked like 50% of herself,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Luke says.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was just numb to everything,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI felt like just a shell of myself. Like, barely existing.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  After Pipe, Caroline took her family\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s advice and left the tour. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSometimes they know me better than I know myself,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI needed to completely let go, and not think about anything else besides working on myself.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Marks went to stay with her parents in Florida. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was really hard on myself,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI felt ashamed for even needing a break.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Her family told her not to. Even if she wanted to quit surfing for good, they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099d love her the same. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cYou should be very proud,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Darren told her, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cthat you were big enough of a human being\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094strong enough of a woman\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094to say,I need this.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  She rested, maybe for the first time since she was 11 years old. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was under so much pressure at such a young age for so long,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was probably always going to happen.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Doing deep work with her psychologist, Marks realized, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI was dealing with depression, 100 percent,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s f---ing gnarly. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 In that dark place, your brain is not functioning properly. And your body\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s like, what\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s going on?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  She quit Instagram, TikTok, Facebook. Researchers have well-documented evidence of social media\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s detrimental effect on teens\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 mental health\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094Meta\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s own studies show teenage girls who struggle with body image issues feel worse after using Instagram. Marks learned, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWhen people are saying mean things, a lot of times it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s coming from a deeper place that isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t even really about the way you look\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s about something to do with them.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Coupled with that, she also learned that she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a people pleaser. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m always wanting to make sure everyone\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s good and happy,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBut it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s impossible to please everyone.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  So she quit trying to. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI just took care of me,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m taking care of me, and honestly doing the best I can do, then what other people say doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t matter.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Caroline went fishing with her brothers. She got a Goldendoodle puppy named Axel. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI just tried to have her focus on having fun,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Luke says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAnd kinda put the whole tour scene out of her head for a bit.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  It worked. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIn California,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI can go train and the waves are always good, but there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s always people around, and there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s always someone you compete against out in the water, and it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s kind of hard to turn your mind off. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 There\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s just something about being home in Florida that feels so grounded.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  And she went surfing with her family, right back where she caught her first waves. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt was so nice going surfing just, behind the house, with nobody else around,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cNobody taking pictures. Nobody else trying to surf with me. Just how we did it growing up.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  After five months away, Marks returned to the tour in June 2022. She kept social media off her phone for another few months; her team posted to her accounts.  She cruised through the end of 2022, finishing in the top five in all four events she entered, and opened \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009923 by placing ninth at Pipeline on Hawai'i\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s North Shore. Then came the Sunset competition, with the bleeding ears, the doctor ordering surgery. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI should\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve seen it coming,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Marks says. She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s suffered sinus and ear infections most of her life. Three years prior, another doctor recommended surgery, to avoid, well, this. But same as she trusted that she needed to step away before\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094now she trusted that she should keep going.  USADA, which sets anti-doping rules for all Olympic and Paralympic sports, prohibits prescription painkillers and antihistamines, leaving Marks to manage her symptoms and pain with over-the-counter medication and holistic treatment. Those methods didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t do much. Nevertheless, she finished the Sunset event by placing second on her 21st birthday, telling reporters she just had a minor ear infection\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094but she was suffering. Throughout the season she postponed multiple flights, spent entire days in bed and went virtually deaf. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe best thing to do was to stay out of the water,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBut I couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t stay out of the water.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  In El Salvador in June, Marks notched her first win in two years. At Teahupo'o in Tahiti in August, she caught one of the best barrels of her life on one of the tour\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s most intimidating breaks. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThat showed me,O.K., you really got this now,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says.  Marks entered September\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s WSL Finals ranked No. 4 in the world. The event was back at her adopted home break, Lower Trestles. After winning the semis to qualify for the 2024 Olympics, the finals put her against none other than Carissa Moore once again, bringing her career full circle. Eight years before, she had surfed a heat against Moore at Lower Trestles in her first tour event. Four years before, she defeated Moore to win her first tour event.  This time, Marks upset Moore to win her first world title. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe just had this demeanor in the water,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Sarah says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe carried herself with this energy that said,This is where I belong.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  One morning in early January, Marks sips coffee in the living room of her two-story San Clemente home; a hairstylist and makeup artist prep her for a photo shoot. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cGlammed up to put on a wetsuit and get in the ocean,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says, laughing. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI should show up like this to Pipeline. You gotta win if you do that, though. You can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t do that and finish, like, third.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  High above San Clemente, windows provide panoramic views of the Pacific Ocean, and Marks\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s home is filled with surfing trophies and memorabilia. On her dining table, there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the World Surf League championship trophy, in all its 75-pound glory. Outside, a sauna covers half the courtyard. In the garage, a just-installed cold plunge tub\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094complete with purple rubber ducky\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094sits in front of three electric bikes, beneath an array of surf jerseys. Fifty-plus surfboards lean against the opposite wall.  After loading her SUV to make for Dana Point, Marks sits in the vehicle for a while to snap selfies. She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s back on Instagram now, and working on a post. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009c \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098POV I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m going surfing\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she asks. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cOr, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098POV going surfing?\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d She laughs and shakes her head. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThese filters are so crazy. I don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t even look real.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Without posting anything, she closes the app and drives.  Naturally, she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s intent this year on winning gold in the Olympics, and then defending her world title. But she has another goal that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s proved even more elusive for her until recently. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m trying to really enjoy the moment and be present as much as I can,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAnd not worry too much about the future, or dwell anymore on things in the past, and just stay focused on what I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m doing right now. The only thing I can control is being a better person. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 And justlive.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Over dinner at Nick\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Restaurant in San Clemente, where she ate kale and quinoa salad with steak three straight nights before the world title, Marks and some friends polish off two bottles of cabernet and gush about Caroline finally allowing herself to just live. She went